
 Nping
		
		nping – Network Packet Generator & Traffic Analysis Tool
		
		Nping is part of the nmap package. It’s installed by default if you install nmap on your Linux system with nping is a network packet generation and response
		analysis tool that comes with Nmap. It allows users to send custom packets, perform latency testing, and conduct network diagnostics.
		The simplest thing you can do with nping is to test if a port of any kind (TCP, UDP, ICMP) is open. 

		# apt-get install nmap
		
		# nping -h 
		
	
Basic nping Commands
		
		
		1. ICMP Ping (Similar to ping)

			# nping --icmp google.com

			• Sends ICMP Echo Requests (like ping) to test connectivity.

			• Useful for network latency checks.

		2. TCP SYN Scan (Similar to hping3 -S)

			# nping --tcp -p 80 192.168.1.1

			• Sends a TCP SYN packet to port 80 of 192.168.1.1.

			• Useful for checking if a port is open.

		3. UDP Ping

			# nping --udp -p 53 192.168.1.1

			• Sends UDP packets to port 53 (DNS) of the target.

			•  Checks if UDP traffic is allowed through firewalls.

		5. Spoofing Source IP (hping3 -a Alternative)

			# nping --tcp -p 443 --source-ip 10.10.10.10 192.168.1.1

			• Spoofs the source IP as 10.10.10.10 when sending TCP packets to port 443.

			• Useful for firewall and intrusion detection testing.

		6. ARP Request (Find MAC Address)

			# nping --arp 192.168.1.1

			• Sends an ARP request to find the MAC address of 192.168.1.1.

			• Useful for network troubleshooting.

		7. High-Speed Packet Flooding (Stress Testing)

			# nping --tcp --rate 1000 -p 80 192.168.1.1

			• Sends 1,000 TCP packets per second to port 80.

			• Used for stress testing or DoS simulation (ethical testing only).



		# nping --arp 192.168.1.1 -c 1													- Send an ARP request to a single IP
		
		# nping --arp 192.168.1.0/24 -c 1												- ARP Scan an Entire Subnet
		
		# nping --arp 192.168.1.20,21,31,41,51 -c 1             - ARP Scan Multiple Specific IPs
		
		# nping --icmp --icmp-type time 192.168.1.20					  - Send an ICMP Time Exceeded Packet
		
		# nping --icmp --icmp-code 0 192.168.1.20							  - Send ICMP Packets with Different Codes  Normal Echo Reply.
		
		# nping --icmp --icmp-code 1 192.168.1.20							  - Destination Unreachable: Host Unreachable.
		
		# nping --icmp --icmp-code 2 192.168.1.20               - Destination Unreachable: Protocol Unreachable.
		
		# nping --tcp - p 80 192.168.1.20  											- Send a TCP SYN Packet to Port 80 (Web Server) Useful to check if a web server is running
		
		# nping --tcp - p 80 --ttl  2 192.168.1.20							- TCP Packet with a Low TTL Used to check hop limits in a network
		
		
		# nping --tcp - p 443 --flags ACK  --ttl  2 192.168.1.20    - TCP ACK Scan on Port 443 (HTTPS)
		
			• --flags ACK → Sends a TCP ACK packet.
			
			• Checks if a port is filtered (firewalled) or open.

			• If no response → port is filtered (blocked by a firewall).

			• If RST response → port is closed.


		# nping --tcp - p 443 --flags FIN  --ttl  2 192.168.1.20		- TCP FIN Scan (Stealth Scan)
		
			• --flags FIN → Sends a TCP FIN packet.
			
			• If no response → port might be open.

			• If RST response → port is closed.
		
		
		# nping --tcp - p 443 --flags RST  --ttl  2 192.168.1.20		- TCP RST Scan (Reset Flag)
		
			• --flags RST → Sends a TCP Reset packet.
			
			• Can be used for connection termination testing.


		# nping --echo-sever “public”													- Echo Server Test
		
			• Uses nping in echo mode, sending packets to a public echo server.

      • The server reflects packets back to test network connectivity.



Summary Table
 
			
| Command                                     | Purpose |
| nping --arp 192.168.1.1 -c 1                | Get MAC address of an IP |
| nping --arp 192.168.1.0/24 -c 1             | Scan MAC addresses in a subnet |
| nping --icmp --icmp-type time 192.168.1.20  | Send ICMP Time Exceeded |
| nping --icmp --icmp-code 0 192.168.1.20     | Send ICMP Echo Reply |
| nping --tcp -p 80 192.168.1.20              | Test if port 80 is open |
| nping --tcp -p 443 --flags ACK 192.168.1.20 | Firewall detection scan |
| nping --tcp -p 443 --flags FIN 192.168.1.20 | Stealth scan (FIN scan) |
| nping --echo-server "public"                | Test packet reflection via an echo server |

